## Dulles Toll Road
### Because You Clearly Need to Get Somewhere, and Somewhere Needs to Take Your Money

The Dulles Toll Road, also known as the Dulles Access Road, is a toll road that connects [Washington Dulles International Airport](/Washington_Dulles_International_Airport) to the [Capital Beltway](/Capital_Beltway) (I-495) in Northern [Virginia](/Virginia), United States. The road is a part of the larger [Dulles Corridor](/Dulles_Corridor) and spans approximately 13 miles (21 km). Because what's a road trip without a toll to make it feel like a real accomplishment?

### History
Because You Want to Know Who to Blame for This Toll

The Dulles Toll Road was first conceived in the 1950s as a way to connect the growing [Washington D.C.](/Washington_D.C.) metropolitan area to the newly constructed Washington Dulles International Airport. The road was built in the early 1960s and opened to traffic in 1962. The construction of the toll road was a joint effort between the [Federal Aviation Administration](/Federal_Aviation_Administration) (FAA) and the [Commonwealth of Virginia](/Virginia).

### Route Description
Because You Clearly Need Directions

The Dulles Toll Road begins at the [Washington Dulles International Airport](/Washington_Dulles_International_Airport) and heads east, passing through the [Chantilly](/Chantilly,_Virginia) and [Herndon](/Herndon,_Virginia) areas. The road intersects with [Virginia State Route 28](/Virginia_State_Route_28) (VA-28) and [Virginia State Route 267](/Virginia_State_Route_267) (VA-267) before merging with the [Capital Beltway](/Capital_Beltway) (I-495). The toll road has several interchanges, including the [Dulles Access Road Interchange](/List_of_interchanges_of_the_Capital_Beltway) with the Capital Beltway.

### Tolls
Because You Knew This Was Coming

The Dulles Toll Road is a toll road, which means you'll have to pay to play. The tolls are collected at the [Dulles Toll Road Main Plaza](/Toll_plaza) and the [Dulles Toll Road On-Ramp Plaza](/Toll_plaza). The tolls are as follows:

* Cash toll: $3.25
* E-ZPass toll: $2.50
* Video toll: $4.00

Don't worry, it's not like you're being robbed or anything.

### Public Transportation
Because You Don't Want to Drive, But You Still Need to Get Somewhere

The Dulles Toll Road is served by several public transportation options, including the [Washington Metro](/Washington_Metro) [Silver Line](/Silver_Line_(Washington_Metro)) and the [Fairfax Connector](/Fairfax_Connector) bus system. Because who needs a car when you can ride the bus?

### Controversies
Because You Knew There Had to Be Some Drama

The Dulles Toll Road has been the subject of several controversies over the years, including concerns about [traffic congestion](/Traffic_congestion), [air pollution](/Air_pollution), and [toll increases](/Toll_road). In 2012, the [Metropolitan Washington Airports Authority](/Metropolitan_Washington_Airports_Authority) (MWAA) approved a plan to increase tolls on the road to help pay for the construction of the [Silver Line](/Silver_Line_(Washington_Metro)) extension. Because who doesn't love a good toll increase?

### Future Plans
Because You Want to Know What's Coming Next

The Dulles Toll Road is expected to undergo several changes in the coming years, including the construction of a new [ interchange](/Interchange_(road)) with [Virginia State Route 28](/Virginia_State_Route_28) (VA-28) and the widening of the road to reduce [traffic congestion](/Traffic_congestion). Because who doesn't love a good road project?

